"Yes, sir. They should be on their way now, we gave them time to get rations from the mess." At exactly 5:00, the Exodus company was gathered at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We are deploying to FOB I-131, eighty kilometers from Ianlos. We must support the ongoing siege and the upcoming attack on Ianlos to quell the rebellion. From there, we will have an advanced position and a base at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Gather your units, and board."
The company dispersed, each joining their unit, and the sergeants made them board the tanks. Cohren climbed onto one of the armored vehicles, at the front of the convoy, and joined Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days earlier, but he knew little about them. Sitting on the side, legs dangling, he adjusted his pack and radio equipment, which was connected to his earpiece and throat mic.
"Hey Cohren, does Harris still have Snowball?" Nemic asked as they settled in.
"You mean the chicken he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning they had stolen it from a farm. "Yes, I'm sure of it."
Cohren looked toward one of the tanks and saw Harris with his unit. From the back of his pack, he could just barely make out the movement of a small chicken shaking its head to observe the surroundings.
"Yeah, he still has it," said Cohren as the tank's turret opened with a clicking sound to allow his commander to pass.
"All the tanks were on the move," declared the commander calmly, but clearly in his helmet. The engines of a platoon of tanks and Strykers roared as they began to advance. The Kronos that Cohren was on shuddered when its brakes were released and it started moving into formation. The tanks spread out in a V to cross the plains of Itania. The winter storms had frozen the swamps and forests, but the mud was still there.
After about an hour, one of the new recruits, named Orson in Cohren's memory, spoke up. "Lieutenant, have you been here since the start of the war, isn't that right?"
"Yeah, Operation Firestorm," replied Cohren. "We thought we could finish it in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Underestimating is a weak word," said Nemic as he joined the conversation. "They had more weapons and men than we had anticipated. They managed to destroy the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Damn, we should see it from where we are."
"Well, I'll hold firm for the Federation," said Orson in a slightly provocative tone. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"You say that now, but from experience, I know that new recruits like you at eighteen years old take cover the moment they hear a shot," declared Craith.
"I think we'll find out soon," said Corhen as he laughed. Orson did not respond to the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We detect thermal signatures at approximately 300 meters, 20 degrees right."
Cohren climbed to the top of the tank and put on his optical glasses. Activating the thermal vision, he could see thermal signatures in the distance.
"Yeah, I see them," Cohren replied through his throat mic.
"Are they enemies?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"Can't tell for sure," declared Cohren. He activated his mic and said: "Exodus Company, don't shoot unless they shoot at you, get them to come out."
As they approached, the small thermal signatures went from blurry spots to more distinct shapes. As they got closer, one of them ran toward something, picked it up, and then rushed back to the small ridge where they were. The silhouettes took positions for shooting.
"We have contacts," shouted Shaw over the radio, as orange tracer rounds were fired from the ridge. Bullets ricocheted off the sides of the tanks, while soldiers jumped from vehicles to take cover behind them. A anti-tank missile whistled past and crashed to the ground behind the formation, exploding and sending debris flying onto one of the vehicles. Another missile hit the side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. Its crew scrambled out and dove for cover as the ammunition ignited.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3," 25 degrees right, 275 meters. "Fire," roared the tank platoon commander over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, their shells flew toward the ridge and exploded, sending mud and stones into the air.
"Send the Senti," cried Knoxx, who was observing the ridge through his binoculars. The back of one of the Cerberus opened and a disarmed soldier wearing a special helmet emerged. He barked orders into a square microphone and two Senti, or Sentinels by their official name, rushed outside. Their thin, metal-armed and -legged bodies swung forward as they sprinted. They were armed, but their weapons were attached to their backs.
"Do we kill them or capture them?" asked Craith as they watched them.
"It seems we are capturing them," said Cohren as the two Sentinels disappeared into a cloud of smoke and ash. Shouts and gunfire echoed from the ridge, but quickly ceased. A moment later, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots dragged along the ground. Once safe with the platoon, they threw the individual to the ground. He groaned in pain as he collapsed into the mud and snow.
Shaw walked toward the individual, who was beginning to get up. He turned to one of the Sentinelles. "How many?"
"Three dead, sir," said the Sentinel. "The others fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing beside him. "Both of you, would you be kind enough to get rid of this man?"
